00:00:04,565 --> 00:00:08,348
and gentlemen, and I welcome you to my GDC 2017 talk

2
00:00:08,348 --> 00:00:10,690
about next level creature sound design.

3
00:00:10,690 --> 00:00:12,892
And before I actually start, may I remind you

4
00:00:12,892 --> 00:00:14,654
to just switch off your phones and maybe put them

5
00:00:14,654 --> 00:00:18,197
into quiet mode or flight mode.

6
00:00:18,197 --> 00:00:20,078
And I think we are ready to go.

7
00:00:21,371 --> 00:00:23,313
So first of all, I want to give you an overview

8
00:00:23,313 --> 00:00:24,553
about what I'm going to talk today.

9
00:00:24,553 --> 00:00:27,556
So obviously it's about next level creature sound design.

10
00:00:27,556 --> 00:00:29,317
And first of all, I'm going to give you an introduction

11
00:00:29,317 --> 00:00:32,239
about myself, why am I kind of the right person

12
00:00:32,239 --> 00:00:34,281
to talk about creature sound design in the first place.

13
00:00:34,281 --> 00:00:36,483
I will give you some initial thoughts

14
00:00:36,483 --> 00:00:37,884
about creature sound design,

15
00:00:37,884 --> 00:00:40,906
because I've been doing this for about the last seven years.

16
00:00:40,906 --> 00:00:44,929
I will also run you through pre-production,

17
00:00:44,929 --> 00:00:47,471
the recording process, the design process,

18
00:00:47,471 --> 00:00:50,513
and also briefly about implementation.

19
00:00:51,574 --> 00:00:55,337
And yeah, so myself, my name's David Phillip,

20
00:00:55,337 --> 00:00:57,359
and I'm a co-founder of Noiseworks Limited,

21
00:00:57,359 --> 00:01:00,981
an audio outsourcing company in London.

22
00:01:00,981 --> 00:01:03,984
And I'm also a Boom Library recordist and designer.

23
00:01:03,984 --> 00:01:07,266
And I worked on a large amount of creature-heavy titles

24
00:01:07,266 --> 00:01:09,268
in my past, so for example, Elder Scrolls Online,

25
00:01:09,268 --> 00:01:10,869
most of you probably know.

26
00:01:10,869 --> 00:01:12,470
Blade and Soul, which is an Asian game,

27
00:01:12,470 --> 00:01:14,131
and Arcania is a German game,

28
00:01:14,131 --> 00:01:15,772
again, a very creature-heavy title.

29
00:01:16,732 --> 00:01:19,573
And over the last four years, or the last two years actually,

30
00:01:19,573 --> 00:01:22,876
I was leading the Creature Sound Effects production

31
00:01:22,876 --> 00:01:25,817
for Total War Warhammer, which I think many of you have played.

32
00:01:25,817 --> 00:01:28,279
And it's, again, a very creature-heavy title.

33
00:01:28,279 --> 00:01:31,341
And I'm very happy to share some insight out of that game

34
00:01:31,341 --> 00:01:33,703
and out of the production with you tonight as well.

35
00:01:33,703 --> 00:01:36,865
Right, so the initial thoughts, I

36
00:01:36,865 --> 00:01:40,687
think that's quite important to ask yourself before you start

37
00:01:40,687 --> 00:01:41,688
designing creature sounds.

38
00:01:41,688 --> 00:01:44,229
So I think the first question I ask myself

39
00:01:44,229 --> 00:01:46,371
is, what's my role as a creature sound designer?

40
00:01:46,860 --> 00:01:50,661
And I think the best way to put it is to create sound for something alive,

41
00:01:50,661 --> 00:01:54,622
where there's not really a reference in the real world,

42
00:01:54,622 --> 00:01:57,463
so you can't just go out and have a look at what a creature sounds like.

43
00:01:57,463 --> 00:01:59,544
That's pretty much impossible.

44
00:01:59,544 --> 00:02:04,666
And that's a very creative process of making that make sense to the audience or the player.

45
00:02:04,666 --> 00:02:09,708
The second question is, what makes a creature more difficult than other sound effects?

46
00:02:10,852 --> 00:02:19,820
It's again a very difficult question in a way, but again, you know, there's no real life reference and that's definitely a tough aspect about the whole thing.

47
00:02:19,820 --> 00:02:30,690
But we're also highly dependent on different layers, which, you know, they can be difficult to blend and, you know, we always have to aim for making a creature sound like one creature, not many at the same time.

48
00:02:31,714 --> 00:02:36,257
And lastly, is there a difference between producing creatures for interactive and linear media?

49
00:02:36,257 --> 00:02:40,060
I mean, obviously we're at GDC, so it's all about gaming, but

50
00:02:40,060 --> 00:02:43,603
some of you might actually have to create creature sounds for FMVs or cutscenes and so on.

51
00:02:43,603 --> 00:02:50,849
And I think the actual production, what we are going to focus on tonight, is actually not that different.

52
00:02:50,849 --> 00:02:54,132
But we're going through that over the course of the next hour anyway.

53
00:02:55,437 --> 00:02:59,422
So after these initial thoughts over the last few years,

54
00:02:59,422 --> 00:03:01,925
I came up with, personally for me,

55
00:03:01,925 --> 00:03:04,688
the three ingredients of great creature sound design,

56
00:03:04,688 --> 00:03:07,091
like almost like a rule book for myself

57
00:03:07,091 --> 00:03:10,115
to create the creature sound designs from.

58
00:03:10,115 --> 00:03:12,899
So the first point, which always is very important for me,

59
00:03:12,899 --> 00:03:13,600
is character.

60
00:03:14,617 --> 00:03:16,298
So you probably ask yourself, what do you mean by character?

61
00:03:16,298 --> 00:03:17,699
Because people come up to me, you know,

62
00:03:17,699 --> 00:03:18,840
they give me feedback on a creature

63
00:03:18,840 --> 00:03:20,461
and say they need much more character,

64
00:03:20,461 --> 00:03:21,441
they don't have enough character.

65
00:03:21,441 --> 00:03:23,362
And I, you know, initially I didn't really know

66
00:03:23,362 --> 00:03:24,863
what they meant.

67
00:03:24,863 --> 00:03:28,405
So character is about how does the creature act?

68
00:03:28,405 --> 00:03:30,046
What's its characteristics, you know?

69
00:03:30,046 --> 00:03:30,687
Is it aggressive?

70
00:03:30,687 --> 00:03:31,647
Is it really stupid?

71
00:03:31,647 --> 00:03:34,629
Is it highly intelligent?

72
00:03:34,629 --> 00:03:36,650
And how do I perceive its emotions?

73
00:03:36,650 --> 00:03:37,611
Or how does it react?

74
00:03:37,611 --> 00:03:40,793
How does it make me feel as a player?

75
00:03:40,793 --> 00:03:44,035
And that's everything on a vocal basis, obviously.

76
00:03:45,205 --> 00:03:48,026
Then the next point, the next very important ingredient

77
00:03:48,026 --> 00:03:48,806
is variation.

78
00:03:48,806 --> 00:03:52,447
So firstly, variation in terms of your articulations.

79
00:03:52,447 --> 00:03:55,248
So for example, attack sounds, death sounds,

80
00:03:55,248 --> 00:03:57,569
pain sounds, idle sounds, all that.

81
00:03:57,569 --> 00:04:01,390
But I think also variation in form of sounds we use.

82
00:04:01,390 --> 00:04:03,270
So again, during the course of the next hour,

83
00:04:03,270 --> 00:04:05,711
we're going to look at different recording techniques

84
00:04:05,711 --> 00:04:08,692
to keep that variation always, you know,

85
00:04:08,692 --> 00:04:09,612
to keep on top of that.

86
00:04:11,135 --> 00:04:14,256
And then the last ingredient is perspective.

87
00:04:14,256 --> 00:04:16,438
So, you know, quite a simple point really,

88
00:04:16,438 --> 00:04:18,239
but it is really important to ask yourself,

89
00:04:18,239 --> 00:04:20,400
where does the sound live in our game?

90
00:04:20,400 --> 00:04:23,461
And in what space, you know, is it always indoors?

91
00:04:23,461 --> 00:04:24,362
Is it outdoors?

92
00:04:24,362 --> 00:04:25,402
Is it in a cave?

93
00:04:25,402 --> 00:04:26,243
And so on.

94
00:04:26,243 --> 00:04:28,104
Is it really close up or very far?

95
00:04:28,104 --> 00:04:29,305
So do we have to, you know,

96
00:04:29,305 --> 00:04:30,165
we have to take care of that as well.

97
00:04:30,165 --> 00:04:33,007
And that all comes together in a term

98
00:04:33,007 --> 00:04:33,967
which I think is very...

99
00:04:35,168 --> 00:04:39,431
very important and I will use it, and I apologize in advance, I will use it a lot tonight, which is

100
00:04:39,431 --> 00:04:43,774
believability. So that's our main aim as a creature sound designer, to make something

101
00:04:43,774 --> 00:04:47,476
which I just mentioned before, which isn't real and which isn't in the real world, to make it

102
00:04:47,476 --> 00:04:51,919
believable for the player and, you know, that results in immersion as well for the player.

103
00:04:51,919 --> 00:04:57,783
So in the next video I'm going to show you a few examples of creature sounds which for me

104
00:04:57,783 --> 00:05:02,306
stand for believability, they just work and they should get you pumped up for the next hour as

105
00:05:02,306 --> 00:05:03,887
well. So let's have a listen to that.

106
00:06:16,912 --> 00:06:19,833
So yeah, I don't know about you, but even the Godzilla roar

107
00:06:19,833 --> 00:06:21,194
still gives me goosebumps actually,

108
00:06:21,194 --> 00:06:22,195
just now it happened again.

109
00:06:22,195 --> 00:06:24,876
So this is just a really good example

110
00:06:24,876 --> 00:06:25,917
of believable creatures, you know,

111
00:06:25,917 --> 00:06:26,918
that you can just feel the size,

112
00:06:26,918 --> 00:06:29,579
you feel the aggression or the intelligence or whatever.

113
00:06:29,579 --> 00:06:31,260
A lot of character and a lot of believability.

114
00:06:31,260 --> 00:06:35,883
Right, so we can actually start on the actual process,

115
00:06:35,883 --> 00:06:37,944
which we start with the pre-production.

116
00:06:37,944 --> 00:06:40,626
And pre-production is actually

117
00:06:40,626 --> 00:06:42,187
one of the most important aspects,

118
00:06:42,187 --> 00:06:43,708
in my opinion, of creature sound design.

119
00:06:44,569 --> 00:06:48,291
And I'm guilty myself of neglecting that process,

120
00:06:48,291 --> 00:06:50,413
and because we always, as sound designers,

121
00:06:50,413 --> 00:06:52,194
we kind of want to jump straight in there

122
00:06:52,194 --> 00:06:53,435
and actually record a design.

123
00:06:53,435 --> 00:06:56,017
So it is mostly overlooked and forgotten about,

124
00:06:56,017 --> 00:06:58,800
but I do think it's very important,

125
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:02,443
because we always have to be aware of what we work on.

126
00:07:02,443 --> 00:07:04,064
I talked about character before,

127
00:07:04,064 --> 00:07:05,765
so that's one part, obviously,

128
00:07:05,765 --> 00:07:07,987
but also what universe is it in,

129
00:07:07,987 --> 00:07:10,749
and the characteristics and skills of the creatures

130
00:07:10,749 --> 00:07:11,510
we're going to work on.

131
00:07:12,490 --> 00:07:15,432
We also need to make ourselves aware of what material we want to use.

132
00:07:15,432 --> 00:07:19,714
So creature sound designs, it stands and falls with the source we are using.

133
00:07:19,714 --> 00:07:21,335
So we want to plan that as well.

134
00:07:21,335 --> 00:07:24,637
One can't paint without colors, it's just, you know, we can't create great sounds without

135
00:07:24,637 --> 00:07:26,979
great material in the first place.

136
00:07:26,979 --> 00:07:30,761
And also I think at this point it's very important to mention that if you're freelance or with

137
00:07:30,761 --> 00:07:32,081
a developer, it doesn't really matter.

138
00:07:32,081 --> 00:07:33,442
Pre-production is always important.

139
00:07:33,442 --> 00:07:37,865
Just that it probably is a bit easier to get the information you need when you're actually

140
00:07:37,865 --> 00:07:39,746
employed by someone or in-house.

141
00:07:41,168 --> 00:07:44,873
Let's look at the pre-production a bit of an advanced way

142
00:07:44,873 --> 00:07:46,155
in terms of creature sound design.

143
00:07:46,155 --> 00:07:48,518
So the first thing I would do is I would find out

144
00:07:48,518 --> 00:07:50,620
the creature's origin, its special characteristics

145
00:07:50,620 --> 00:07:51,341
and skills.

146
00:07:51,341 --> 00:07:54,325
So I mentioned before, for example,

147
00:07:54,325 --> 00:07:56,588
a creature can be highly intelligent,

148
00:07:56,588 --> 00:08:00,673
it could be super stupid, it could be, you know,

149
00:08:01,148 --> 00:08:03,630
Again, it could be very big, it could be very small,

150
00:08:03,630 --> 00:08:04,970
and it could have special skills,

151
00:08:04,970 --> 00:08:06,691
like for example, a dragon could have a fire breath.

152
00:08:06,691 --> 00:08:08,452
I need to know about that.

153
00:08:08,452 --> 00:08:11,473
And I need to search, look for the dialogue

154
00:08:11,473 --> 00:08:13,655
between myself and the design team

155
00:08:13,655 --> 00:08:15,876
to find out about the special characteristics

156
00:08:15,876 --> 00:08:17,316
of a creature in the first place.

157
00:08:18,158 --> 00:08:20,519
Then I want to know how does it produce sound in the first place.

158
00:08:20,519 --> 00:08:22,720
Does it have a voice box?

159
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:26,661
Because I've dealt with creatures before who were actually ghostly and before actually

160
00:08:26,661 --> 00:08:29,822
reading about this creature I wouldn't know how they would actually produce the sound.

161
00:08:29,822 --> 00:08:32,883
And that's again something which dictates the way I'm working.

162
00:08:32,883 --> 00:08:35,223
Is there a need for language?

163
00:08:35,843 --> 00:08:40,965
that's a very uh tricky situation actually to be in and it happened to us in in Warhammer

164
00:08:40,965 --> 00:08:45,627
because we are creatures who communicated with one another and that's you know I can't really

165
00:08:45,627 --> 00:08:50,529
deal with that and with my attack sounds and my death sounds so that normally is very important

166
00:08:50,529 --> 00:08:54,570
to know and would in our case would go to the dialogue team and they would deal with that

167
00:08:54,570 --> 00:08:58,712
but again if you you know if you get to that information very late on in the process

168
00:08:58,712 --> 00:08:59,772
you probably run out of time.

169
00:09:01,060 --> 00:09:03,481
Size and their scale in relation to other creatures in game.

170
00:09:03,481 --> 00:09:04,701
So this is also a very important one.

171
00:09:04,701 --> 00:09:06,022
As you've seen before in the video,

172
00:09:06,022 --> 00:09:08,123
you saw Khaleesi's dragon on her shoulder,

173
00:09:08,123 --> 00:09:12,625
very small compared to Godzilla, which is obviously massive.

174
00:09:12,625 --> 00:09:14,165
But if you just see a screenshot of the game,

175
00:09:14,165 --> 00:09:16,086
you know, you see the dragon and you see Godzilla,

176
00:09:16,086 --> 00:09:18,127
you probably wouldn't be able to tell the difference

177
00:09:18,127 --> 00:09:20,148
between them in size.

178
00:09:20,148 --> 00:09:22,309
And again, it's very important to check beforehand

179
00:09:22,309 --> 00:09:24,990
because it's very difficult after you've created

180
00:09:24,990 --> 00:09:26,470
a full set of creature sounds

181
00:09:26,470 --> 00:09:29,092
to make the sounds very small or very big afterwards.

182
00:09:29,954 --> 00:09:31,836
And all this will come together

183
00:09:31,836 --> 00:09:33,377
and define the sonic character of your creatures.

184
00:09:33,377 --> 00:09:35,079
And again, think about the three main ingredients,

185
00:09:35,079 --> 00:09:38,542
characters, definitely one of the most important ones.

186
00:09:38,542 --> 00:09:40,584
So if you, I hope you can see that.

187
00:09:40,584 --> 00:09:42,966
I put like a few example notes together

188
00:09:42,966 --> 00:09:45,829
of how I normally approach creature sound.

189
00:09:45,829 --> 00:09:47,690
In this case, I called it random dragon.

190
00:09:48,371 --> 00:09:50,713
You can see that on the top left there.

191
00:09:50,713 --> 00:09:51,854
And for example, I put down,

192
00:09:51,854 --> 00:09:53,715
I always do a little bit of a mind map.

193
00:09:53,715 --> 00:09:55,496
So first of all, it's just for me,

194
00:09:55,496 --> 00:09:58,619
but later on it's really useful to share this information

195
00:09:58,619 --> 00:10:02,201
with my coworkers who might have to work on their creature

196
00:10:02,201 --> 00:10:02,842
if it's not myself.

197
00:10:02,842 --> 00:10:05,744
So in terms of the large dragon here,

198
00:10:05,744 --> 00:10:07,505
the random dragon, sorry, it's a large size.

199
00:10:07,505 --> 00:10:09,687
It's very aggressive, it's highly intelligent,

