00:40:34,334 --> 00:40:37,356
and then, you know, the high elements would lose all their bass,

724
00:40:37,356 --> 00:40:40,838
and with the bass layers I would try and emphasize their bass,

725
00:40:40,838 --> 00:40:43,319
and then at the end I'd get to something like this, and I'm very happy,

726
00:40:43,319 --> 00:40:46,762
but then I have to do five or six variations, and I'm again very sad.

727
00:40:46,762 --> 00:40:47,342
So, um...

728
00:40:48,709 --> 00:40:51,211
Yeah, I think that's a good example of how it's been broken down.

729
00:40:51,211 --> 00:40:55,693
And, you know, this is actually an example where I used quite a lot of different layers

730
00:40:55,693 --> 00:41:01,417
because I try sometimes to limit myself because obviously the less layers I use, the easier

731
00:41:01,417 --> 00:41:04,158
it gets for me to actually get them work together.

732
00:41:05,593 --> 00:41:13,579
Right, so after the pre-production part, the recording part, and also the design part, we do

733
00:41:13,579 --> 00:41:18,863
have to look into implementation, which is the last part of the process, apart from the mix,

734
00:41:18,863 --> 00:41:24,246
obviously. And I think it's so important these days that if the implementation is bad, even the

735
00:41:24,246 --> 00:41:30,611
best sound can't save it. So it does make me very upset if I spend that much time on a sound.

736
00:41:30,771 --> 00:41:33,752
you know, like weeks or maybe a week or two weeks,

737
00:41:33,752 --> 00:41:35,773
and then in the end in the game,

738
00:41:35,773 --> 00:41:39,455
it just doesn't sound the way I expect it to sound.

739
00:41:39,455 --> 00:41:41,336
So we are dependent on great systems for sounds

740
00:41:41,336 --> 00:41:42,737
to make them shine properly.

741
00:41:42,737 --> 00:41:44,598
We really have to, you know,

742
00:41:44,598 --> 00:41:46,859
this is very important that they actually do,

743
00:41:46,859 --> 00:41:48,900
in Pro Tools or in your DAW, they sound great,

744
00:41:48,900 --> 00:41:50,281
but as soon as they come in the game,

745
00:41:50,281 --> 00:41:52,121
there's so many different factors,

746
00:41:52,121 --> 00:41:54,443
and obviously the mix has to work around it,

747
00:41:54,443 --> 00:41:56,784
and it's really important to get stuck into implementation.

748
00:41:57,564 --> 00:42:01,227
So in my opinion, implementation is 50% the experience.

749
00:42:01,227 --> 00:42:03,768
Again, it's completely useless to spend all this time

750
00:42:03,768 --> 00:42:06,390
and all these processes if the implementation is bad.

751
00:42:06,390 --> 00:42:10,373
But I also have to say there's countless possibilities

752
00:42:10,373 --> 00:42:11,473
of implementing audio.

753
00:42:11,473 --> 00:42:13,275
So anyone who worked in games before

754
00:42:13,275 --> 00:42:15,476
knows that there's so many different things.

755
00:42:15,476 --> 00:42:17,137
There's Wwise, there's FMOD, there's

756
00:42:17,137 --> 00:42:18,438
so many different engines.

757
00:42:18,438 --> 00:42:21,840
Every company works with different tools.

758
00:42:21,840 --> 00:42:24,822
And therefore, I can't, unfortunately, just

759
00:42:24,822 --> 00:42:26,063
show you everything about the.

760
00:42:26,843 --> 00:42:31,228
about implementing creature sounds, but what I decided to do is actually to give you again

761
00:42:31,228 --> 00:42:35,872
some tips which helped me in the past, especially when working on Total War Warhammer, a very

762
00:42:35,872 --> 00:42:40,336
creature heavy game, you know, for you just to maybe gain some inspiration from.

763
00:42:42,530 --> 00:42:48,335
So I think in terms of creature sound design, the hierarchy set up is incredibly important.

764
00:42:48,335 --> 00:42:53,059
So again in terms of Warhammer, we had small, medium, large and extra large and huge creatures.

765
00:42:53,059 --> 00:42:58,243
So again this is a hierarchy decision we had to make very early on in the process

766
00:42:58,243 --> 00:43:03,208
because you know many people work on that game and we have to later on mix that stuff as well.

767
00:43:03,208 --> 00:43:06,310
So it's very important to always keep that kind of hierarchy together,

768
00:43:06,310 --> 00:43:08,192
almost like the layers of a creature sound design.

769
00:43:08,973 --> 00:43:11,635
Because it does make it easier in the end

770
00:43:11,635 --> 00:43:13,797
to make the large creature sounds bigger

771
00:43:13,797 --> 00:43:16,479
than everything else and not to lose yourself

772
00:43:16,479 --> 00:43:19,982
in the hierarchy in the end.

773
00:43:19,982 --> 00:43:21,504
Another very interesting aspect,

774
00:43:21,504 --> 00:43:23,085
which unfortunately I don't really have time

775
00:43:23,085 --> 00:43:24,767
to get too much into today,

776
00:43:24,767 --> 00:43:28,390
is the modular approach versus the one-shot approach.

777
00:43:28,390 --> 00:43:30,272
So everything I've showed you today

778
00:43:30,272 --> 00:43:32,033
was all based on one-shot.

779
00:43:32,033 --> 00:43:34,215
So for example, I have an attack animation,

780
00:43:34,215 --> 00:43:35,336
I make this attack sound.

781
00:43:35,697 --> 00:43:37,457
and it would just, you know, I put a trigger point

782
00:43:37,457 --> 00:43:40,718
into the animation, it would play in game and happy days.

783
00:43:40,718 --> 00:43:42,998
But sometimes it can be necessary

784
00:43:42,998 --> 00:43:44,638
that there's so many different animations,

785
00:43:44,638 --> 00:43:47,259
a basic sound set of articulations,

786
00:43:47,259 --> 00:43:49,539
like I showed you before of my random dragon example

787
00:43:49,539 --> 00:43:51,660
with 42 sounds, would just not do it

788
00:43:51,660 --> 00:43:53,620
because there's too many animations

789
00:43:53,620 --> 00:43:57,801
and they would just not sync tightly to the animations.

790
00:43:57,801 --> 00:44:00,841
So what we tried to do in some cases with Warhammer

791
00:44:00,841 --> 00:44:02,842
and with other games as well is that we tried to,

792
00:44:02,842 --> 00:44:03,802
for example, a scream.

793
00:44:04,682 --> 00:44:06,744
we would divide them up in three parts,

794
00:44:06,744 --> 00:44:10,146
like a start sound, a middle sound, and a stop sound,

795
00:44:10,146 --> 00:44:13,928
which makes it, of course, that's great for variation purposes,

796
00:44:13,928 --> 00:44:17,290
but anyone who has tried to blend them in-game before,

797
00:44:17,290 --> 00:44:18,351
it's, again, quite tricky.

798
00:44:18,351 --> 00:44:20,633
So you have to lay a problem in the first place,

799
00:44:20,633 --> 00:44:23,414
and then you also have to blend between those three parts

800
00:44:23,414 --> 00:44:24,915
in the game engine, which can be tricky.

801
00:44:24,915 --> 00:44:27,477
But again, if you pull it off, it sounds amazing in-game

802
00:44:27,477 --> 00:44:31,119
because you have the best amount of variation.

803
00:44:31,880 --> 00:44:35,860
Distant versus close assets, I think that's a very basic thing to say.

804
00:44:35,860 --> 00:44:40,721
It probably seems a bit stupid to talk about it, but I think it's incredibly important,

805
00:44:40,721 --> 00:44:45,982
again, if we think about the three main ingredients of our perspective, that we always, as a rule,

806
00:44:45,982 --> 00:44:48,943
and I don't know who set that rule, but whenever I start a creature sound design,

807
00:44:48,943 --> 00:44:53,023
I start with a close-up, close to the camera kind of sound.

808
00:44:53,023 --> 00:44:57,164
But sometimes it would actually be good to start with a distant sound before

809
00:44:57,164 --> 00:44:59,705
and then work yourself, you know, towards the close sound.

810
00:45:00,345 --> 00:45:03,909
And how we solved that in Wwise before is that we just had a closed sound,

811
00:45:03,909 --> 00:45:06,471
we had a distant sound which was created after closed sound,

812
00:45:06,471 --> 00:45:09,975
but sometimes had to lose some of the layers to actually make it sound distant.

813
00:45:09,975 --> 00:45:12,217
So again, another problem we were facing.

814
00:45:12,217 --> 00:45:17,843
And then we just blend them over distance and with in-game parameters like a cue or reverb.

815
00:45:19,123 --> 00:45:21,284
Use of cone attenuation I think was something

816
00:45:21,284 --> 00:45:24,365
which really changed the way we were mixing our games as well.

817
00:45:24,365 --> 00:45:26,726
So you can imagine that like a cone coming out

818
00:45:26,726 --> 00:45:29,247
of the creature's mouth.

819
00:45:29,247 --> 00:45:30,968
And whenever it turns away from the camera,

820
00:45:30,968 --> 00:45:32,508
the perspective would change accordingly.

821
00:45:32,508 --> 00:45:34,769
And you can automate the EQ, not automate,

822
00:45:34,769 --> 00:45:37,730
but the game engine would deal with the EQ settings,

823
00:45:37,730 --> 00:45:40,011
like low pass and high pass and all that.

824
00:45:40,011 --> 00:45:42,372
And it would just, again, work on the believability

825
00:45:42,372 --> 00:45:45,113
of our game and work on the believability of our creature

826
00:45:45,113 --> 00:45:45,313
sound.

827
00:45:46,103 --> 00:45:48,405
Volume equals size, make use of it.

828
00:45:48,405 --> 00:45:50,406
This is another really basic thing.

829
00:45:50,406 --> 00:45:52,547
And you probably laugh about it if I tell you that,

830
00:45:52,547 --> 00:45:55,328
you know, obviously large creatures should be

831
00:45:55,328 --> 00:45:57,369
louder than small creatures.

832
00:45:57,369 --> 00:45:59,230
But I don't know why it happens so much,

833
00:45:59,230 --> 00:46:00,991
but if I look at a hierarchy,

834
00:46:00,991 --> 00:46:02,191
small, medium, large creatures,

835
00:46:02,191 --> 00:46:04,012
every starting point is actually zero dB

836
00:46:04,012 --> 00:46:06,673
or minus 10 or whatever, but they're all equal.

837
00:46:07,013 --> 00:46:10,695
And it's actually a good starting point to just, you know, do that gain staging

838
00:46:10,695 --> 00:46:14,376
in a really simple way beforehand because it just really

839
00:46:14,376 --> 00:46:16,636
makes the whole mixing process so much easier in the end.

840
00:46:16,636 --> 00:46:21,578
And another thing, the sweetener layers, which is something we made use of heavily,

841
00:46:21,578 --> 00:46:24,178
not just for creature sounds but also for other sound effects.

842
00:46:24,178 --> 00:46:28,700
But for example, if we had big dragon sound, like the huge creatures, like the giants and the dragons.

843
00:46:29,160 --> 00:46:31,282
we could actually, if they're very close to the camera,

844
00:46:31,282 --> 00:46:33,464
we would play a sweetener sound on top of that,

845
00:46:33,464 --> 00:46:36,066
something we created just for that effect

846
00:46:36,066 --> 00:46:40,390
to add a proximity effect, which could be a stereo sound

847
00:46:40,390 --> 00:46:43,032
or a quad sound even to really fill out that space

848
00:46:43,032 --> 00:46:46,255
and to make that huge creature, which is already huge,

849
00:46:46,255 --> 00:46:48,236
make even more huge, because that's what we want.

850
00:46:48,236 --> 00:46:51,119
We want to make everything sound really loud and powerful.

851
00:46:52,358 --> 00:46:55,165
So yeah, we are pretty much at the end of my presentation.

852
00:46:55,165 --> 00:46:57,792
I'll just give you a summary of the most important aspects

853
00:46:57,792 --> 00:46:59,556
what I've been talking about today.

854
00:47:00,725 --> 00:47:02,526
Again, pre-production is key.

855
00:47:02,526 --> 00:47:04,168
You definitely have to know what you're working on.

856
00:47:04,168 --> 00:47:07,090
I think it's, again, very important to mention

857
00:47:07,090 --> 00:47:09,772
that pre-production is important,

858
00:47:09,772 --> 00:47:13,035
and it is worth it reading all the books

859
00:47:13,035 --> 00:47:15,777
about the creatures, get to know their characteristics

860
00:47:15,777 --> 00:47:18,099
and special skills, because it will pay off

861
00:47:18,099 --> 00:47:21,102
in your recording process later on, and also in the design,

862
00:47:21,102 --> 00:47:22,543
and you will always be in brief,

863
00:47:22,543 --> 00:47:23,784
or most of the time anyway.

864
00:47:27,067 --> 00:47:30,971
Be creative with the recording process, but sometimes the most simple approach can get

865
00:47:30,971 --> 00:47:34,195
the most satisfying result, trial and error.

866
00:47:34,195 --> 00:47:38,240
So again, with the recording process, it's all about recording as much as you can, you

867
00:47:38,240 --> 00:47:42,605
know, really don't be scared to go out there and just record all day, edit it up, put it

868
00:47:42,605 --> 00:47:46,149
in your library, and then later on you can choose from that stuff.

869
00:47:46,149 --> 00:47:48,111
I can't stress enough how important it is to...

870
00:47:48,271 --> 00:47:53,995
really, you know, have enough source to choose from. Because when I talk to, to some of you

871
00:47:53,995 --> 00:47:58,939
guys beforehand, before this actual talk, the first question I've always, or I'm most of the

872
00:47:58,939 --> 00:48:04,323
time being asked is, what plugins do you use? And again, I think my plugin and my plugin is

873
00:48:04,323 --> 00:48:09,066
the source. And I think nobody can take that away from you if you really record as much as

874
00:48:09,066 --> 00:48:09,526
possible.

875
00:48:10,831 --> 00:48:14,793
Pitch matching EQ and volume, those three ingredients work with good source.

876
00:48:14,793 --> 00:48:18,235
So again, this is in terms of the design process, obviously.

877
00:48:18,235 --> 00:48:20,697
Stick with those three things for a start.

878
00:48:20,697 --> 00:48:24,359
You know, match the pitch, EQ the elements you want to,

879
00:48:24,359 --> 00:48:27,340
and then do the volume offsets, do some fades.

880
00:48:27,340 --> 00:48:30,382
And I'm pretty sure it will get you far away.

881
00:48:30,382 --> 00:48:33,964
And I think it's, you know, and afterwards you can use all the plugins in the world,

882
00:48:33,964 --> 00:48:38,227
but just make sure that the first step is always pitch matching EQ and volume.

883
00:48:39,653 --> 00:48:43,337
And I think most importantly, get stuck into implementation if you can.

884
00:48:43,337 --> 00:48:45,880
If you're freelance, at least try to get involved.

885
00:48:45,880 --> 00:48:48,843
So I'm now in a position where I'm freelance again.

886
00:48:48,843 --> 00:48:53,268
And I do want to make sure that my sounds end up in the game as intended

887
00:48:53,268 --> 00:48:55,871
and to sound as good as possible, obviously.

888
00:48:55,871 --> 00:49:00,776
And if you're in-house, talk to the implementation team.

889
00:49:01,768 --> 00:49:04,350
Sorry, get stuck into implementation.

890
00:49:04,350 --> 00:49:06,231
Obviously in the in-house it's much easier

891
00:49:06,231 --> 00:49:08,012
because you're actually on the spot

892
00:49:08,012 --> 00:49:10,274
and you don't have to write as many emails

893
00:49:10,274 --> 00:49:11,775
as I have to do normally.

894
00:49:11,775 --> 00:49:15,397
And then finally, believability and character,

895
00:49:15,397 --> 00:49:18,039
the most important aspects of creature sound design.

896
00:49:19,458 --> 00:49:23,901
If you think about what we're trying to achieve with, you know, the whole creating games in the first place,

897
00:49:23,901 --> 00:49:29,866
we want to create a universe for the player to get immersed in and, you know, to feel at home in a way.

898
00:49:29,866 --> 00:49:34,609
And that's exactly what we're trying to do, what we're trying to achieve with our creature sounds as well.

899
00:49:34,609 --> 00:49:41,634
To make them believable and, you know, to kind of define their character of something which isn't real in the real world,

900
00:49:41,634 --> 00:49:44,776
but obviously real because designers designed it.

901
00:49:44,776 --> 00:49:46,658
So it's all about believability and character.

902
00:49:48,036 --> 00:49:52,603
So, yeah, thank you very much for your attention.

903
00:49:52,603 --> 00:49:54,826
I think that's pretty much it.

